    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-04-25T22:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-04-25T22:00:00-05:00" n="111"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d111">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.20 Defense (M) Portugal/1475a: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Brazil</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Caffery</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-04-25T23:00:00-04:00"
                            >April 25, 1944—11 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1325. The British and American Governments are deeply concerned over the
                    continued exports of wolfram from Portugal to Germany. As this mineral is vital
                    to German tank, munitions and armament production the war is being prolonged and
                    the lives of allied troops sacrificed by the continued shipments from the
                    Iberian Peninsula, the bulk of which come from Portugal. The Department is
                    informed that total German wolfram requirements for this year <pb facs="0112"
                        n="102" xml:id="pg_102"/> are estimated at 3,000 tons and that it appears
                    that she will obtain about 2,000 tons from Portugal and Spain.</p>
                <p>In view of Brazil’s particularly close ties with Portugal and considering
                        Aranha’s<note n="63" xml:id="d111fn1">Oswaldo Aranha, Brazilian Minister for
                        Foreign Affairs.</note> and João Neves’<note n="64" xml:id="d111fn2"
                        >Brazilian Ambassador in Portugal.</note> assurances of their readiness to
                    help us in Portugal, you are requested to explore the possibilities of Brazilian
                    assistance at Lisbon in this matter. We feel confident that Brazil will be as
                    anxious as we are to reduce, in so far as possible, this help to our common
                    enemy.</p>
                <p>Ambassador Martins,<note n="65" xml:id="d111fn3">Carlos Martins, Brazilian
                        Ambassador in the United States.</note> with whom this problem has been
                    discussed, is sending a parallel message to the Itamaraty.<note n="66"
                        xml:id="d111fn4">Seat of Brazilian Foreign Office.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
